#. type: Hash Value: methods agent_per_infection
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The agent-per-infection rate measures how frequently specific pathogens are detected relative to the number of infections in which any infectious agent was identified. Values above 100% are expected and indicate polymicrobial infections. Diagnostic challenges specific to neonates — including low blood volume reducing culture sensitivity and elevated contamination risk — may influence detection patterns."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods ci_quartile_auto_note
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Bootstrap confidence intervals for reference quartiles are displayed only for metrics where quartile values are not suppressed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods ci_quartile_bootstrap
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Confidence intervals for reference quartiles are computed using a parametric bootstrap that propagates both within-department sampling uncertainty and cross-department distributional uncertainty. Department-level rates are resampled 2,000 times using non-informative prior distributions, and quartiles are recalculated for each iteration. The reported bounds represent the 2.5th and 97.5th percentiles of the bootstrap distribution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods ci_rates
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Confidence intervals for rates use exact Poisson methods when the denominator is an exposure measure (such as patient-days or device-days) and Wilson score intervals when the denominator is a count of discrete entities (such as the number of infections or pathogens tested). Both methods provide reliable coverage for small counts including zero."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods device_associated
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Device-associated infections are defined by a time-based association according to the NeoIPC Core Protocol: a vascular catheter must have been in place for at least three consecutive days, and ventilatory support for at least four calendar days, before an infection on that day or the day before qualifies as device-associated. This represents a temporal rather than a proven causal relationship. The denominator is device-days — only days on which the device was present."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods heading
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Methodology"
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods incidence_density
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Incidence density rates are calculated per 1,000 patient-days, allowing comparison between departments with different patient volumes and lengths of stay. The primary sepsis/BSI category includes both clinical sepsis and laboratory-confirmed bloodstream infections."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods infectious_agent_detection
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The infectious agent detection rate measures the proportion of infections in which at least one infectious agent was identified. Higher detection rates for sepsis/BSI may reflect thorough microbiological workup practices. Lower detection rates for NEC are expected because the NEC surveillance definition is based on radiological and clinical criteria, and pathogens are only recorded when a secondary bloodstream infection occurs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods patient_population
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Birth weight and gestational age are the primary case-mix descriptors in neonatal surveillance. Lower birth weight and earlier gestational age are associated with increased vulnerability to healthcare-associated infections. The figures show both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles and pooled arithmetic mean)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods pooled_rate
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The pooled rate is the arithmetic mean across all individual records in the reference population. Because it is calculated at the patient level rather than as an average of department-level rates, the pooled rate can fall outside the interquartile range, which is derived from department-level rates."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods quartiles
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reference data quartiles represent the 25th percentile (Q₁), median (Q₂) and 75th percentile (Q₃) of department-level rates. Quartiles are displayed only when at least five departments contribute to the denominator and the metric is frequent enough that a typical department would be expected to observe at least one event based on the pooled rate. When these conditions are not met, quartiles are suppressed to avoid presenting unreliable distributional estimates."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods resistance_test
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) rate measures the proportion of eligible pathogens for which a resistance test result was recorded. Low AST rates may indicate gaps in microbiological diagnostic capacity and can limit the ability to detect resistant organisms."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods resistant_pathogens
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "This section reports the rate at which detected pathogens carry specific resistance markers. An empty table indicates that no resistant organisms were detected among tested pathogens — it does not indicate that testing was not performed. Resistance testing completeness is reported separately in the antimicrobial susceptibility testing section."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods risk_density
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exposure density rates measure the number of days a risk or protective factor was present per 100 patient-days. Device and ventilation days require the device or support to be in place for at least 12 hours on that calendar day. A human milk day requires that the patient's enteral feeding exclusively consists of human milk (including donor milk and fortified breast milk). Probiotic days require an oral probiotic containing Lactobacillus spp. or Bifidobacterium spp. A kangaroo care day is recorded when the patient received intensive skin-to-skin contact for at least 2 hours on a given calendar day. Antibiotic days are counted from the first dose to the last dose of a therapy inclusive, including days where doses were skipped, but not days after the last dose. Antibiotic exposure is recorded per individual substance. For reporting, substance-days are aggregated into WHO AWaRe categories (Access, Watch, Reserve); combination therapy means a single patient-day may contribute substance-days to multiple categories."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods secondary_bsi
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "A secondary bloodstream infection is a BSI attributed to a site-specific infection (pneumonia, NEC, or SSI) when the same organism is identified within a 17-day window around the primary infection (3 days before through 13 days after). Catheter-associated infections are excluded. Secondary BSI rates tend to have small event counts, which frequently leads to quartile suppression."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods sparse_data
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rates based on small numbers of events are inherently unstable and may not reflect systematic patterns. Where this applies, individual table rows are flagged accordingly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Hash Value: methods surgical_procedures
#: reports/common.yaml:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Surgical procedure rates are calculated per 100 patients, not per 1,000 patient-days. One patient may contribute multiple procedures."
msgstr ""

