#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "`r if (has_reference) \"This is a [NeoIPC Surveillance](https://neoipc.org/surveillance/)<!-- --> analysis of infection rates in your neonatal department, presented alongside reference data from the NeoIPC Surveillance network to support benchmarking and identification of areas for further review.\" else \"This is a [NeoIPC Surveillance](https://neoipc.org/surveillance/)<!-- --> analysis of infection rates in your neonatal department. This report does not include reference data for benchmarking. It can be used to monitor your department's infection rates over time and to establish a local baseline. For reference data from the NeoIPC Surveillance network, see the Reference Report published at <https://neoipc.org/surveillance/resources/>.\"`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following summary presents key surveillance metrics for this report:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_patient-population.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The NeoIPC surveillance system focuses on high-risk neonates to ensure sustainable continuous monitoring. Patients with a birth weight below 1500 g and/or gestational age below 32 weeks at birth are included if admitted within the first 120 days of life. The following figures show the composition of your patient population based on the filter settings specified in the report header.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_nosocomial_infections.Rmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Healthcare-associated infections represent the primary endpoint of NeoIPC surveillance. In your department, `r dR$own$numberOfSevereInfections` severe infections were recorded in `r dR$own$numberOfPatients` patients, resulting in an average of `r dR$own$averageSevereInfectionsPerPatient` infections per patient`r if (!is.null(dR$ref)) paste0(\", compared to \", dR$ref$numberOfSevereInfections, \" infections in \", dR$ref$numberOfPatients, \" reference patients (average: \", dR$ref$averageSevereInfectionsPerPatient, \")\")`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_nosocomial_infections.Rmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following tables present incidence density rates for sepsis/bloodstream infections, pneumonia, and necrotizing enterocolitis, as well as device-associated infection rates.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_infectious-agents.Rmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding the epidemiology of infectious agents causing nosocomial infections is crucial but complex. Diagnostic challenges including low sensitivity (limited blood volume) and specificity (contamination risk) are inherent to the neonatal population. Additionally, availability of microbiological diagnostics and resources can significantly affect detection rates.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_infectious-agents.Rmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "In your data, `r dR$own$numberOfInfectiousAgents` infectious agents were detected in `r dR$own$numberOfInfectionsWithAgent` infections out of `r dR$own$overallNumberOfInfections` total infections (including sepsis/BSI, pneumonia, necrotising enterocolitis, and surgical site infections), representing an infectious agent detection rate of `r dR$own$infectiousAgentDetectionRate` per 100 infections. The following tables provide detailed information on pathogen distribution and antimicrobial resistance patterns.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_risk-factors.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exposure to invasive devices, ventilatory support, antibiotics, and protective interventions significantly influences infection risk in neonatal intensive care. The following subsections present utilization rates for these factors and for surgical procedures performed in your department.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_surgery.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Surgical interventions in neonates carry inherent infection risks. The following subsection presents rates for various surgical procedures performed in your department.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_diagnostics.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reliable interpretation of infectious agent and resistance data depends on the completeness and quality of microbiological diagnostics. The following subsections provide indicators to help assess whether observed pathogen and resistance patterns reflect true epidemiology or are shaped by diagnostic practices.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction-caution.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rates based on small numbers of events should be interpreted with caution, as they are inherently unstable and may not reflect systematic patterns. This applies to any rate in this report, whether in your department's data or the reference data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_fig-intro-birth-weight.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Birth weight distribution is a key indicator of your department's patient population characteristics. Understanding the weight distribution of admitted neonates helps contextualize infection rates and other outcomes, as lower birth weight is associated with increased vulnerability to healthcare-associated infections. @fig-bw shows both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles) of birth weights in your department, enabling comparison with your patient case mix relative to reference data when available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_fig-intro-gestational-age.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Gestational age distribution provides essential context for interpreting clinical outcomes in your neonatal department. Extremely premature infants face substantially higher risks of complications and infections compared to more mature neonates. @fig-ga illustrates both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles) of gestational ages at birth, allowing you to assess how your patient population's maturity profile compares to reference data when available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-incidence-density.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "@tbl-incidence-density-rates presents the incidence density rates for the most important healthcare-associated infections (HAI) in your neonatal department. Incidence density rates are calculated per 1,000 patient days, allowing for meaningful comparison between departments with different patient volumes and lengths of stay. The primary sepsis/BSI category includes both clinical sepsis and laboratory-confirmed bloodstream infections (LCBSI). Regular monitoring of these rates enables you to identify trends, evaluate the effectiveness of infection prevention measures, and compare your performance against reference data from other participating departments.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-device-associated.qmd:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Device-associated infections represent a significant burden in neonatal intensive care. @tbl-device-associated-incidence-density-rates shows infection rates associated with central venous catheters (CVC), peripheral venous catheters (PVC), invasive ventilation (INV), and non-invasive ventilatory support (NIV). By tracking device-associated infection rates separately, you can assess the safety of device utilization in your department and identify specific areas where targeted interventions may reduce infection risk. Lower rates may indicate successful implementation of device care bundles and infection prevention protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced div block ({.callout-note})
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-device-associated.qmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Device-associated infections are defined by a time-based association according to the\n"
"[NeoIPC Core Protocol](https://neoipc.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/NeoIPC-Surveillance_Core-Module-Protocol.pdf):\n"
"a device must have been in use for a defined period prior to infection.\n"
"This represents a temporal rather than a proven causal relationship.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-agent-per-infection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding which pathogens cause infections in your department is essential for targeted prevention strategies and empirical treatment decisions. @tbl-agent-per-infection-rate presents the detection rates of infectious agents per infection type, highlighting the microbial epidemiology of healthcare-associated infections in your neonatal population. Patterns in pathogen distribution can inform antimicrobial stewardship efforts and help identify potential sources of transmission requiring specific control measures.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-abr-infection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Antimicrobial resistance poses a critical threat to vulnerable neonatal patients. @tbl-abr-infection-rate displays infection rates caused by resistant pathogens such as MRSA, VRE, and third-generation cephalosporin-resistant organisms. This section reports *detected* resistant pathogens in infections; @tbl-resistance-test-rate reports how completely susceptibility testing was performed. Both are needed to interpret resistance burden. Monitoring these rates is crucial for assessing the burden of drug-resistant infections in your department and evaluating the effectiveness of antimicrobial stewardship programs. Elevated rates may signal the need for enhanced infection control measures, antibiotic prescribing review, or environmental screening protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-infectious-agent-detection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The pattern of pathogen detection across different infection types provides valuable insights into your department's microbial ecology. @tbl-infectious-agent-detection-rate shows how frequently specific infectious agents are identified in various types of healthcare-associated infections. Understanding these detection patterns helps in developing targeted surveillance strategies, appropriate empirical therapy guidelines, and infection prevention protocols tailored to your department's specific pathogen profile.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-resistance-test.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST) is fundamental to both individual patient management and population-level surveillance. @tbl-resistance-test-rate presents the rate at which pathogens isolated from infections undergo testing for certain relevant antimicrobial resistances. This section assesses testing *completeness*; @tbl-abr-infection-rate reports the detected resistant pathogens themselves. High testing rates ensure reliable data for antimicrobial stewardship programs and enable accurate assessment of resistance trends. Lower rates may indicate gaps in microbiological diagnostic capacity or protocols that could limit your ability to detect and respond to emerging resistance patterns.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-risk-density.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "@tbl-risk-density-rates shows the utilization density of key interventions including invasive devices, ventilatory support, antibiotics, and protective measures such as human milk feeding, kangaroo care, and probiotics. Benchmarking these utilization rates helps identify opportunities to reduce unnecessary device use while optimizing evidence-based protective interventions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-surgical-procedure.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "@tbl-surgical-procedure-rates presents rates of various surgical procedures performed in your department, normalized per 100 patients. Understanding your surgical case mix is essential for interpreting infection rates and implementing appropriate surgical site infection prevention protocols. Comparison with reference data helps contextualize your department's surgical workload and associated infection risks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-secondary-bsi.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "A secondary bloodstream infection is a BSI that is seeded from a site-specific infection (pneumonia, NEC, or SSI) at another body site, except for catheter-associated infections. @tbl-secondary-bsi-rates shows the rate at which a secondary BSI is attributed to different primary infection types based on the NeoIPC criteria (organism match within a 17-day window around the primary infection). High rates of secondary BSI may indicate delayed diagnosis, inadequate source control, or particularly virulent pathogens, and warrant careful review of clinical protocols and infection management strategies.\n"
msgstr ""

